\begin_layout Standard
With the isolated nanowire model built, we are left to account for the supercond
uctivity proximity effects.
 Foremost, we specify the superconductor to be of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-type.
 In nontrivial topological cases, the order parameter has a vortex profile
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(x)=\Delta_{0}(x)e^{i\varphi(x)}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 the magnitude of the superconducting energy gap, roughly represents the
 energy required to break a Cooper pair, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

 a factor that the superconducting wavefunction acquires spontaneously below
 the transition temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 due to the 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)$
\end_inset

 symmetry breaking.
 For our 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-wave SCs, the superconducting gap has isotropic magnitudes and phases,
 hence we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}(x)\equiv\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)\equiv\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 We can then describe the proximity effects between the SM and SCs as Cooper
 pairs tunneling into the nanowire inducing a pairing potential of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta(x)=\Delta_{0}\Theta(x-L)+\Delta_{0}e^{i\varphi}\Theta(-x-L)\label{eq:OP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 the Heaviside function.
 These correlations can then be described with the Hamiltonian density
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}_{\text{SC}}=\frac{1}{2}\Delta(x)\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}^{*}(x)\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}^{*}(x)+c.c.\label{eq:H_SC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color green
Notice that complex conjugation (instead of a hermitian conjugation) is
 sufficient since we said to be working with a 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-wave SC.

\color inherit
 Finally, the Hamiltonian density describing the whole system is given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=\mathcal{H}_{\text{SM}}+\mathcal{H}_{\text{SC}}$
\end_inset

, reading explicitly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{H} & =\psi_{\alpha}^{*}\left(-\eta\partial_{x}^{2}-\mu+i\alpha_{\text{R}}\sigma_{y}\partial_{x}+V_{\text{Z}}\sigma_{x}\right)\psi_{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\Delta\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}^{*}\psi_{\tilde{\beta}\downarrow}^{*}+\frac{1}{2}\Delta^{*}\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}\psi_{\tilde{\beta}\uparrow}\label{eq:H_nw}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we omitted every spacial dependency (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\alpha}\equiv\psi_{\alpha}(x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\equiv\Delta(x)$
\end_inset

, etc...).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
BdG Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the system's Hamiltonian described, we can now try to find a way to
 determine its eigenstates and corresponding eigenenergies.
 For this we make the preparation for Bogoliubov-de Genes (BdG) theory.
 In order to formalize this general framework, we start by compactly describing
 the Hamiltonian density in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:H_nw}}$
\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{H} & =\sum_{\alpha\beta}\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}h_{\alpha\beta}\psi_{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{\tilde{\alpha}\tilde{\beta}}\left(\Delta\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}^{*}\psi_{\tilde{\beta}\downarrow}^{*}+\Delta^{*}\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}\psi_{\tilde{\beta}\uparrow}\right)\label{eq:H_nw_c}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Our task is to express this Hamiltonian in it's Bogoliubov-de Genes (BdG)
 form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\frac{1}{2}\Psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}\mathcal{H}_{\text{BdG}}\Psi_{\beta},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\alpha}\equiv\Psi_{\alpha}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the eigen-vectors of the BdG Hamiltonian with real eigen-energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{BdG}}\Psi_{\alpha}=E_{\alpha}\Psi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Although we are considering a BCS type SC and already specified the fact
 that the Cooper pair electrons have flipped spins in this type of SCs,
 it's useful to generalize the treatment allowing for pairing of same spin
 electron, for reasons we will see in just a moment.
 We are, however, still considering an isotropic order parameter.
 The Hamiltonian density reads instead
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}h_{\alpha\beta}\psi_{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\Delta_{\alpha\beta}\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}\psi_{\beta}^{\dagger}+\Delta_{\alpha\beta}^{*}\psi_{\alpha}\psi_{\beta}\right)\label{eq:Hg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the repeated indices signify a sum over them as is often done in Einstein
 notation.
 
\color green
See that, and following the comment after Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:H_SC}}$
\end_inset

), we must now use hermitian conjugation (instead of just complex conjugation)
 on the anomalous terms.

\color inherit
 Following the convection for Nambu spinors, one could initially assume
 the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 to be just 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\alpha}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}\\
\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 However, while a static, zero energy mode could be obtained from this choice,
 for the finite energy modes, we must take account of the fact that both
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}$
\end_inset

 mix with their complex conjugates.
 Therefore, one cannot separate the time dependence with just an overall
 energy phase.
 Correspondingly one cannot construct a Hamiltonian energy eigenvalue problem,
 which is the usual first step in the quantization procedure.
 The solution to this issue is then to double the system's degrees of freedom
 by writing a four-component Nambu spinor in the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi_{\alpha}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}\\
\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}\\
\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}^{*}\\
-\psi_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}^{*}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\alpha}\\
i\sigma_{y}\psi_{\alpha}^{*}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\alpha}\\
\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notice that we didn't define the antiparticle field of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 as simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\alpha}^{*}$
\end_inset

 since this conflicts with the Dirac field under Lorentz transformations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\alpha}\rightarrow e^{iS_{\mu\nu}\omega^{\mu\nu}}\psi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mu\nu}=\nicefrac{i}{4}[\gamma_{\mu},\gamma_{\nu}]$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 the angular momentum operator.
 Instead, in order to reconcile this discrepancy, we need to defined the
 charge conjugation through the time-reversal operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta=\mathcal{T}\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=e^{i\pi Sy}$
\end_inset

 is a real skew-symmetric matrix, reading 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=i\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

 for the case of spin 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 particles, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 is complex conjugation, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}=i\sigma_{y}\psi_{\alpha}^{*}$
\end_inset

, which is is guaranteed from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\Theta,\mathcal{H}\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
 One the other hand, particle-hole symmetry is expressed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xi=\sigma_{y}\tau_{y}\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 which is guaranteed instead by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Xi,\mathcal{H}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to write the Hamiltonian in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:Hg}}$
\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger} & \psi_{\alpha}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\boldsymbol{h} & \boldsymbol{\Delta}^{*}\\
\boldsymbol{\Delta} & -\sigma_{y}\boldsymbol{h}^{*}\sigma_{y}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{\alpha}\\
\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}
\end{array}\right),\label{eq:HBdGg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we used that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{h}$
\end_inset

 is hermitian, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{h}^{T}=\boldsymbol{h}^{*}$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Delta}=\Delta(x)\mathds{1}$
\end_inset

 is skew-symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Delta}=-\boldsymbol{\Delta}^{T}$
\end_inset

, which is enforced from the fermionic statistics.
 Furthermore, because the last two components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 are constrained by their relation to to the first two, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 satisfies the pseudo reality constrain 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ab}\Psi_{b}=\Psi_{a}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left(0\,\mathds{1}_{2\times2},\,\mathds{1}_{2\times2},\,0\right)$
\end_inset

 having properties 
\begin_inset Formula $C=C^{-1}=C^{*}=C^{T}=C^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, where the new index reads as 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv(\alpha,g)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\pm$
\end_inset

 the Nambu 
\emph on
g
\emph default
rading such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\alpha+}=\psi_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\alpha+}=\psi_{\alpha}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
 The fermionic commutation relations of the field 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset


\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 translate into
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \Psi_{a},\Psi_{b}\right\} =C_{ab}\text{ and }\left\{ \Psi_{a},\Psi_{b}\right\} =\delta_{ab}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Furthermore, fermionic statistics enforces that 
\emph on
any 
\emph default
BdG Hamiltonian expressed as in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:HBdGg}}$
\end_inset

) always possesses the conjugation symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $-\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}^{*}=C^{*}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}C$
\end_inset

.
 From this underlying symmetry emerges the particle-hole symmetry since
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}\Phi=E\Phi\Rightarrow\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}(C\Phi^{*})=-E(C\Phi^{*})\Rightarrow\Phi_{-E}=C\Phi_{+E}^{*}$
\end_inset

, meaning that positive and negative eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}$
\end_inset

 are paired.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now a unitary transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}$
\end_inset

 under which 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
 In this basis we would have that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}^{*}=\tilde{C}^{*}\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}\tilde{C}$
\end_inset

 so that the transformation law for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 reads as 
\begin_inset Formula $C\rightarrow\bar{C}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}C\boldsymbol{\mathcal{U}}^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 See that, if one can appropriately choose a unitary basis such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{C}=\mathds{1}_{4\times4}$
\end_inset

 one can have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}=-\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}^{*}$
\end_inset

 meaning that, in this basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}$
\end_inset

 is purely imaginary or, equivalently, that 
\begin_inset Formula $i\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}$
\end_inset

 is purely real.
 Therefore, from Schrödinger's equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\partial_{t}+i\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}\right)\tilde{\Psi}=0$
\end_inset

, we know that the field's equation of motion would be purely real and thus
 admits purely real solution.
 Moreover, notice that in this basis the commutation relations become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \bar{\Psi}_{a},\bar{\Psi}_{b}\right\} =\bar{C}_{ab}=\delta_{ab}\text{ and }\left\{ \bar{\Psi}_{a},\bar{\Psi}_{b}\right\} =\delta_{ab}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

corresponding to real fermions acting as their own antiparticle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}_{a}=\bar{\Psi}_{a}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, known as 
\emph on
Majorana
\emph default
 fermions.
\end_layout

