\end_inset

 In this case, we can make the ansatz of a plane-wave solution 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ikx}\Psi$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 being the momentum along the wire.
 The Hamiltonian and it's energy-momentum band dispersion (obtained directly
 by solving the characteristic equation) then reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{h}\equiv\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\eta k^{2}-\mu & V_{\text{Z}}+i\alpha_{\text{R}}k\\
V_{\text{Z}}-i\alpha_{\text{R}}k & \eta k^{2}-\mu
\end{array}\right)\text{, with }E_{\pm}(k)=\left(\eta k^{2}-\mu\right)\pm\sqrt{V_{\text{Z}}^{2}+\alpha_{\text{R}}^{2}k^{2}}.\label{eq:En}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Foremost, as shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:En}}$
\end_inset

), we see that the effect of the spin-orbit coupling is the separation of
 the spectrum into two different bands, corresponding to spin-up and spin-down
 bands.
 We see that in the absence of the Zeeman field, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}=0$
\end_inset

, the spectrum consists of two shifted parabolas (at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 they will coincide) but as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}$
\end_inset

 grows the parabolas shift further apart.
 crossing at momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

.
 As the Zeeman field is turned on, the level crossing disappears with the
 opening of a gap 
\begin_inset Formula $2V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

.
 We note that such a gap may also occur due to strong electron-electron
 interactions [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "2.9"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "2.10"
literal "false"

\end_inset

], and thus one could define 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 as accounting for either a magnetic field perpendicular to the spin orbit
 coupling or an interaction induced gap or both.
 Within the 
\begin_inset Formula $2V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 gap the spin is fixed and cannot flip.
 
\color purple
Furthermore, since the spin is given by the momentum direction, the nanowire
 is said to be in the helical regime.
 Also, if the chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 resides within the 
\begin_inset Formula $2V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 gap we have a spinless regime.

\color inherit
 In this case, a large gap is ideal since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 could slightly vary along the wire, for example, due to disorder, without
 leaving this regime.
 It should be noted that the best way to enlarge this gap is to handpick
 a material with a large 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

-factor such that we don't need to apply a huge magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{x}$
\end_inset

 since this could force align spins, making it extra difficult to induce
 superconductivity.
 
\end_layout

