In this particular case the superconducting term reads simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Delta}=\Delta_{0}\left(\Theta(x-L)-\Theta(-x-L)\right)\mathds{1}\equiv\bar{\Delta}\mathds{1}$
\end_inset

 and consequently, the BdG Hamiltonian becomes purely real, reading
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}=\left(-\eta\partial_{x}^{2}+i\alpha_{\text{R}}\sigma_{y}\partial_{x}-\mu\right)\tau_{z}+V_{\text{Z}}\sigma_{x}+\bar{\Delta}\tau_{x}\label{eq:HBdG_pi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From here on out, we will be making the distinction of real variants of
 complex quantities with a hat bar, in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}(\varphi=\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 If the BdG Hamiltonian is real, we are able to construct real Nambu spinors
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Also, with this choice of phase, and assuming the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, describing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\ll\xi$
\end_inset

 physical case, the order parameter in forms a domain wall, as shown in
 Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:JJ}}$
\end_inset

), which under certain conditions will be able to host a pair of Majorana
 fermions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To demonstrate this, we investigate the existence of zero-energy solution
 (actually zero-energy, not just zero-eigenvalue) by solving 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}}_{\text{BdG}}\bar{\Psi}(x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally, and according to the particle-hole symmetry, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 is a solution then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{y}\tau_{y}\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\bar{\Psi}=\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

) is also a solution.
 Therefore, the only way to define a non-degenerate 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{y}\tau_{y}\bar{\Psi}=\pm\bar{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{y}\tau_{y})^{2}=-\mathds{1}_{2\times2}$
\end_inset

 imposed the constrain 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, fixing a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 allows one to define the reduced spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}=\left(\bar{\psi}_{\uparrow},\,\bar{\psi}_{\downarrow}\right)$
\end_inset

 using the constrain on the spin degrees of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}_{\uparrow/\downarrow}^{*}=\lambda\bar{\psi}_{\uparrow/\downarrow}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding reduced BdG equation can be reduced to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix differential equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-\eta\partial_{x}^{2}-\mu & V_{\text{Z}}+\lambda\bar{\Delta}+\alpha_{\text{R}}\partial_{x}\\
V_{\text{Z}}-\lambda\bar{\Delta}-\alpha_{\text{R}}\partial_{x} & -\eta\partial_{x}^{2}-\mu
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow}\\
\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\downarrow}
\end{array}\right)=0.\label{eq:BdG2x2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can then seek solutions of Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:BdG2x2}}$
\end_inset

) in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow/\downarrow}(x)\propto e^{\zeta x}$
\end_inset

 and require solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\lessgtr0$
\end_inset

 to be normalized whilst forcing the boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Psi}(0^{-})=\bar{\Psi}(0^{+})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x}\bar{\Psi}(0^{+})=\partial_{x}\bar{\Psi}(0^{+})$
\end_inset

 at the domain wall.
 Let us focus on the 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 case.
 Physical solutions will then require that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Re}\left\{ \zeta\right\} <0$
\end_inset

 to guarantee a exponentially decaying solution.
 Also, with 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Delta}=\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 .
 The characteristic equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 following Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:BdG2x2}}$
\end_inset

) reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\zeta^{4}+4m^{*2}\left(\mu+\alpha_{\text{R}}^{2}\right)\zeta^{2}+8\lambda m^{*2}\alpha_{\text{R}}\Delta_{0}\zeta+4m^{*2}C_{0}=0\text{ with }C_{0}=\mu^{2}+\Delta_{0}^{2}-V_{\text{Z}}^{2}\label{eq:Ce}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Being a quartic equation, the complete solution will read as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}_{\tilde{\alpha}\uparrow/\downarrow}(x)=\sum_{i=1}^{4}C_{i}e^{\zeta_{i}x}$
\end_inset

, where the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the above quartic equation with real coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 should satisfy the following constrains: 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=i}^{4}\zeta_{i}=4m^{*2}C_{0}\text{ and }\sum_{i=1}^{4}\zeta_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.

\color blue
 Where does this come from? From generic quartic solutions? 
\color inherit
This forces that, for example, if there is at least one complex solution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{1}=a+ib$
\end_inset

 then one other solution must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{2}=\zeta_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, since the other two solutions must follow from the constrains above,
 one can find these roots to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{3,4}=-a\pm\sqrt{a^{2}-4m^{*2}C_{0}/(a^{2}+b^{2})}$
\end_inset

.
 Fixing different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\pm1$
\end_inset

 will just change the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.

\color blue
 Why? Again, from generic quartic solutions?
\color inherit
 The remarkable feature of this model is that, for a fixed values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

, depending on the tuning of the gate controlled chemical potential 
