\begin_layout Standard
Consider an equilibrium many-body system of electrons described by the Hamiltoni
an
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
H_{\text{eq}} & =H_{0}+H_{\text{int}}=\sum_{\alpha\beta}h_{\alpha\beta}c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}c_{\beta}+\sum_{\alpha\beta\gamma\delta}V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta}c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}c_{\beta}^{\dagger}c_{\gamma}c_{\delta},\label{eq:H2quantum}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{\dagger}(c)$
\end_inset

 fermionic creation (annihilation) operators and the Greek indices representing
 generic degrees of freedom.
 Concerning the interaction term, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 to be generic electrostatic potential of symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=V(\mathbf{r}^{\prime}-\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 such that the interaction matrix elements have the symmetries
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta}=V_{\delta\gamma}^{\beta\alpha}\quad\text{and}\quad\left(V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta}\right)^{*}=V_{\alpha\beta}^{\gamma\delta}.\label{eq:Vsym}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


