\begin_layout Standard
However, since we are looking for superconducting solutions, we wish to
 account also for the anomalous terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}c_{\beta}^{\dagger}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle c_{\gamma}c_{a}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 For this, we introduce a Nambu representation as in Ref.(
\color blue
Nambu, 1959
\color inherit
) where we consider the fermionic operators to be defined as spinors in
 spin space as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{c}_{\alpha}(t)\equiv\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{c}
c_{\alpha}(t)\end{array}\\
c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}(t)
\end{array}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Nambu representation of the rDM can then be written as the tensor product
 of this spinors for each of the spin combinations,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\rho}_{ab}\equiv\left\langle \boldsymbol{c}_{b}^{\dagger}(t)\otimes\boldsymbol{c}_{a}(t)\right\rangle \equiv\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\left\langle c_{b}^{\dagger}c_{a}\right\rangle  & \left\langle c_{b}c_{a}\right\rangle \\
\left\langle c_{b}^{\dagger}c_{a}^{\dagger}\right\rangle  & \left\langle c_{b}c_{a}^{\dagger}\right\rangle 
\end{array}\right]\equiv\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}} & \rho_{ab}^{\text{eh}}\\
\rho_{ab}^{\text{he}} & \rho_{ab}^{\text{hh}}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:rDM_def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and omitted the time-dependency in both the rDM and fermionic operators
 for clarity.
 These terms are related by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ab}^{\text{hh}}=-\left(\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}}\right)^{\dagger}+\delta_{ab}\quad\text{\text{and}}\quad\rho_{ab}^{\text{he}}=-\left(\rho_{ab}^{\text{eh}}\right)^{\dagger}\label{eq:rDM_rel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a BCS superconductor, i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-wave and spin-singlet, the pairing terms must have opposing spin however
 this is not the only possible type of superconductivity and thus, to keep
 the problem as general as possible we account for all the four terms.

