\left\langle c_{\alpha}c_{\beta}^{\dagger}c_{\gamma}^{\dagger}c_{\delta}\right\rangle  & \approx\rho_{\beta\alpha}^{\text{hh}}\rho_{\delta\gamma}^{\text{ee}}-\rho_{\gamma\alpha}^{\text{hh}}\rho_{\delta\beta}^{\text{ee}}+\rho_{\delta\alpha}^{\text{eh}}\rho_{\gamma\beta}^{\text{he}}\\
\left\langle c_{\alpha}^{\dagger}c_{\beta}c_{\gamma}c_{\delta}^{\dagger}\right\rangle  & \approx\rho_{\beta\alpha}^{\text{ee}}\rho_{\delta\gamma}^{\text{ee}}-\rho_{\gamma\alpha}^{\text{ee}}\rho_{\delta\beta}^{\text{hh}}+\rho_{\delta\alpha}^{\text{he}}\rho_{\gamma\beta}^{\text{eh}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

As derived in details in the Appendix, the rDM equation of motion can then
 be written in a time-dependent Hartree-Fock in a more compact and elegant
 manner as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{ee}}=\left[\mathbf{H}_{\text{HF}},\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{ee}}\right]-\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{eh}}\boldsymbol{\Delta}^{\dagger}+\boldsymbol{\Delta}\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{he}}\label{eq:EoM_n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, for the normal terms, we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{\text{HF}}$
\end_inset

 as the Hartree-Fock Hamiltonian
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{H}_{\text{HF}}\equiv\bm{h}+\bm{B}\cdot\mathbf{F}(t)+\bm{\Sigma}^{H}+\bm{\Sigma}^{F}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\emph default
identifying the Hartree 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{H}$
\end_inset

and Fock 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{F}$
\end_inset

 self-energy terms respectively as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Sigma_{ab}^{H}\equiv\Sigma_{ab}^{H}[\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{ee}}(t)] & =V_{\gamma b}^{a\delta}\rho_{\gamma\delta}^{\text{ee}},\label{eq:selfH}\\
\Sigma_{ab}^{F}\equiv\Sigma_{ab}^{F}[\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{ee}}(t)] & =-V_{b\gamma}^{a\delta}\rho_{\gamma\delta}^{\text{ee}},\label{eq:selfF}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and the anomalous self-energies, also known as pairing, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Delta_{ab}\equiv\Delta_{ab}[\boldsymbol{\rho}_{\text{eh}}(t)] & \equiv V_{\delta\gamma}^{ab}\rho_{\gamma\delta}^{\text{eh}}\label{eq:selfD}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Notice that the Fock self-energy term in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:selfF}}$
\end_inset

) is an attractive interaction (due the negative sign) such that it lower
 the total energy of the system enabling the formation of bound electron-hole
 states.
 Intuitively, the source of this attractive term can be thought as due to
 the opposing charges of the electron and hole.
 Conversely, the Hartree self-energy term will control details of the excitation
 spectrum, such as spin-splitting (which will be discussed further in the
 text).
 
\color blue
