\begin_layout Subsection
Ultra-localized orbitals approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider the explicit expression of the interaction term written
 in an arbitrary electronic basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi_{\alpha}(\mathbf{r})\right\} $
\end_inset

 in real space as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta}=\int d\mathbf{r}d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\alpha}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\beta}^{*}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\gamma}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\delta}(\mathbf{r})\label{eq:V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 to be a generic electrostatic potential with symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=V(\mathbf{r}^{\prime}-\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, it is from this very same symmetry that the relations we initially
 imposed in Eqs.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:Vsym}}$
\end_inset

) come from.
 Furthermore, consider that we are working with a crystalline system, such
 that we can specify one of the generic degrees of freedom to be a position
 vector in the lattice 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\left(\mathbf{R}_{\alpha},\mathbf{s}_{\alpha},\tilde{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 specifying the position within the Bravais lattice, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{s}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the respective sub-lattice and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 so we don't forget other generic degrees of freedom that the system might
 have.
 Moreover, if we consider a tight-binding (TB) framework and consider the
 orbitals to be ultra-localized, we can reasonably assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 will not vary strongly within the orbital spread and thus, we could factor
 out 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 from the integral in Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:V}}$
\end_inset

), allowing us to write the interaction simply as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\gamma\delta}^{\alpha\beta}\approx V(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\int d\mathbf{r}\phi_{\alpha}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\phi_{\delta}(\mathbf{r})\int d\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\phi_{\beta}^{*}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})\phi_{\gamma}(\mathbf{r}^{\prime})=V(\mathbf{r}_{\alpha}-\mathbf{r}_{\beta})\delta_{\alpha\delta}\delta_{\beta\gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we used the orthogonal property of the orbitals and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}\equiv\mathbf{r}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\equiv\mathbf{r}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 being the centers of the orbitals 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Within the scope of this approximation, the self-energies defined in Eqs.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:selfH}}$
\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:selfD}}$
\end_inset

) now simply read as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Sigma_{ab}^{H}\approxeq & V(\mathbf{r}_{a}-\mathbf{r}_{\gamma})\rho_{\gamma\gamma}^{\text{ee}}\delta_{ab}\\
\Sigma_{ab}^{F}\approxeq & -V(\mathbf{r}_{a}-\mathbf{r}_{b})\rho_{ab}^{\text{ee}}\\
\Delta_{ab}\approxeq & V(\mathbf{r}_{a}-\mathbf{r}_{b})\rho_{ab}^{\text{eh}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

It is important to note that the Hartree term, contrarily to the Fock term,
 does not depend on the distance between the ultra-localized orbitals but
 rather on the purely electronic background density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\text{ee}}$
\end_inset

.
 One can interpret this as if the two orbitals would interact indirectly
 through the effects of the variations of the background density.
 In these sense, the Hartree term would already account for the screening
 dynamics of the system.
 This, however, cannot be said the same for the Fock term.
 Thus, if ones wishes to introduce some screening effect, one must add it
 manually; for example, by choosing, instead of a bare potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, an effective screening potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\rightarrow W(\mathbf{r},\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Technically, to account for the dynamics of the screening, one would have
 to solve the BSE self-consistently since now the Fock self-energy itself
 would depend on the resulting excitonic dynamics.
